            "@type": "dctypes:Text",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><em><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">DC.XIII.L1<br /></span></em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri,sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"><strong>Agnes and her father? Yes</strong><br /><br /></span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri,sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">The left-hand page of this Working Note (which includes memoranda about Agnes and Mr. Wickfield, Mrs. Heep, and the death of Mr. Spenlow) clearly registers the installment&rsquo;s preoccupation with parental failure. The testamentary neglect of a self-proclaimed &ldquo;indulgent father&rdquo; (DC 561) in chapter 38 is placed alongside the &ldquo;weak indulgence&rdquo; (DC 584) of another in chapter 39, and Uriah&rsquo;s story of his childhood leads David to comment that Uriah&rsquo;s &ldquo;detestable cant of false humility might have originated out of the Heep family&rdquo; (DC 581).</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri,sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Evidently, Dickens took great care weaving this thread through the installment: he had prepared readers well early in the installment Miss Murdstone&rsquo;s observation of \"how little disposition there usually is\" among fathers \"to acknowledge the conscientious discharge of duty\" (DC 556). Furthermore, he took great care in heavily revising Mr. Wickfield&rsquo;s lengthy meditation on his failure in the manuscript (\"I have infected everything I touched. I have brought misery on what I dearly love...\" [DC 584]). The number&rsquo;s attention to paternal incapacity pairs well with Dickens&rsquo;s intention in No. XV to &ldquo;shew the faults of mothers, and their consequences&rdquo; (DC_WN_15; see <em>DC.XV.R1</em>).</span></p>",
